In `platform/browser-extension/src/side-panel/components/PluginIcon.tsx` at line 85:
```
const svgToRender = rawSvg ? sanitizeSvg(rawSvg) : undefined;
```

`sanitizeSvg` (in `platform/browser-extension/src/sanitize-svg.ts`) does regex tokenization and string processing. While robust for normal input, pathological SVG strings could cause it to throw (e.g., malformed markup triggering regex edge cases). An unhandled exception here propagates through PluginIcon → PluginCard → PluginList → App, hitting only the top-level ErrorBoundary, which replaces the ENTIRE side panel with an error screen — all because of one broken plugin icon.

**The fix:** Wrap the sanitizeSvg call in a try-catch:
```
let svgToRender: string | undefined;
try {
  svgToRender = rawSvg ? sanitizeSvg(rawSvg) : undefined;
} catch (err) {
  console.warn(`[opentabs] sanitizeSvg failed for plugin "${pluginName}":`, err);
}
```

When `svgToRender` is `undefined` (either because rawSvg was falsy or because sanitizeSvg threw), the existing code already falls through to the letter-avatar branch (line 88: `if (hasSvg && svgToRender)`).

Note: `hasSvg` is set from `!!iconSvg` which will still be true even if sanitizeSvg threw. So the condition `hasSvg && svgToRender` correctly evaluates to `true && undefined` = falsy, falling through to the avatar. No change needed to the conditional logic.

For the test, mock `sanitizeSvg` to throw and verify that PluginIcon renders the letter avatar instead of throwing. The test file is `platform/browser-extension/src/side-panel/components/__tests__/PluginIcon.test.tsx` (or create it if it doesn't exist — check for existing test files in that directory first with `ls platform/browser-extension/src/side-panel/components/__tests__/`).
